Here for the sake of this example imagine that x1 is the data you have fit your vectorizer on. The x2 and x3 are the new out of sample texts. 
We could fit all the texts we have to the vectorizer right away, but that would be wrong: the new texts x2 and x3 will change the scores and biase the vectorizer. In some cases you may want to avoid that for logical reasons: you do not want the new text to infuence the training set. In other cases, at the time of training you simply do not have the new texts. 

Here is what is going on in this code:

1. create lists for training texts (x1) and new out of sample texts (x2 anf x3);
2. initiate TfidfVectorizer;
3. fit and transform training data and make a df out of the resulting scores; (just so that it's nice to look at);
4. transform the first out of sample text and get the scores for it;
5. transform the secondout of sample text and get the scores for it;
6. "Look and you will see!" (or read the explanation below).
